Insurers typically retain a small percentage of the risks they underwrite and pass on the rest of the losses.Insurers buy this insurance protection for themselves by giving up a portion of the premiums they collect on a policy to another firm -- a reinsurance company, which, in turn, accepts a portion of any losses resulting from this policy
