Wall Street is seething over the rules.The provisions could further cool the takeover boom that has been the driving force behind the bull market in stocks for much of the 1980s
At issue is the deductibility of certain junk bonds that are used in most LBOs.Such high-yield debt is similar to a zero-coupon bond in that it is sold at a discount to face value, with interest accruing instead of being paid to the holder
Such high-yield debt is similar to a zero-coupon bond in that it is sold at a discount to face value, with interest accruing instead of being paid to the holder.Under current rules, that accrued interest is deductible by the company issuing the debt
The House version of the legislation would kill that deduction, and label any such debt as equity, which isn't deductible.The less-rigorous Senate version would defer the deductibility for roughly five years
You see these in just about every LBO.It becomes a source of cash" for the company making the LBO because it gets a deduction and doesn't have to repay the debt for several years
Typically, Mr. Willens estimates, this type of debt makes up 15% to 20% of the financing for LBOs.These types of bonds have been used in buy-outs of companies such as RJR Nabisco Inc., Storer Communications Inc. and Kroger Co
But that rule is being virtually overlooked by Wall Street, which is concentrating on coping with the deduction issue. "Prices for LBOs have to come down if you don't have that feature
the proposed legislation already is having an impact.An investment group led by Chicago's Pritzker family recently lowered a $3.35 billion bid for American Medical International, Beverly Hills, Calif., because of the threat of the legislation
