Stock-index arbitrage is the most controversial form of program trading because it accelerates market moves, if not actually causing them.In it, traders buy or sell stocks and offset those positions in stock-index futures contracts to profit from fleeting price discrepancies
In it, traders buy or sell stocks and offset those positions in stock-index futures contracts to profit from fleeting price discrepancies.Under the exchange's definitions, program trading also describes a number of other strategies that, in the opinion of some traders, don't cause big swings in the market
