When Maj. Moises Giroldi, the leader of the abortive coup in Panama, was buried, his body bore several gunshot wounds, a cracked skull and broken legs and ribs.They were the signature of his adversary, Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega
The rebel officer's slow and painful death was personally supervised by Gen. Noriega.Leaping into rages, sinking into bouts of drunkenness and mistrust, Mr. Noriega has put to death some 70 of his troops involved in the coup, according to U.S. officials monitoring crematoriums and funeral parlors in Panama City
He is now changing the place he sleeps every night, sometimes more than once a night.His meals are most often prepared by women he trusts -- his full-time mistress, Vicky Amado, and her mother, Norma
And he is collecting the names of those who telephoned the coup-makers to congratulate them during their brief time in control of his headquarters.More enemies to be dealt with
