In his peaked military cap and neatly pressed, French-made uniform, Noriega felt more respected and powerful than ever in his underprivileged life.He had an elegant uniform with gold buttons in a country where there was a cult of militarism, where officers were the elite with special privileges
Mr. Noriega's relationship to American intelligence agencies became contractual in either 1966 or 1967.His commanding officer at the Chiriqui Province garrison, Major Omar Torrijos, gave him an intriguing assignment: Mr. Noriega would organize the province's first intelligence service
